[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | End-to-end latency (X-ray) | 15-30 seconds from study complete to worklist update |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | End-to-end latency (CT volume) | 60-180 seconds depending on slice count |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | ICH detection sensitivity | 90-95% at 5% false positive rate |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Pneumothorax detection sensitivity | 85-92% at 5% false positive rate |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | PE detection sensitivity | 80-90% at 10% false positive rate |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | System availability target | 99.9% (triage is safety-critical) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost per CT study | ~$1.00-$2.00 (GPU inference dominant) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost per X-ray study | ~$0.10-$0.30 |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Subtle findings at the threshold of human detection (small subdural hematomas, subsegmental PE)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Studies with significant motion artifact or poor contrast timing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Unusual anatomy (post-surgical, congenital variants) that the model hasn't seen in training
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Multi-finding studies where one critical finding masks another
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Edge cases in modality routing (combined studies, non-standard protocols)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Multi-modality radiology AI triage is one of those systems where the ML is actually the easy part. Training a good ICH detector or pneumothorax classifier is well-understood. The hard parts are everything around the model: DICOM integration, worklist modification, PACS vendor cooperation, FDA clearance per indication, and (most importantly) radiologist trust.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The false positive problem is existential for these systems. I've seen deployments where the AI flagged 15-20% of studies as "urgent" in the first week. Radiologists ignored it by day three. You need to be ruthlessly conservative with your confidence thresholds at launch. It's better to miss a few true positives initially and build trust than to flood the worklist with false alarms and lose credibility permanently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The PACS integration is where projects die. Every PACS vendor (GE, Philips, Siemens, Fuji, Sectra, Agfa) has a different integration model. Some have open APIs. Some require custom HL7 interfaces. Some require you to go through their marketplace. Budget 3-6 months just for the integration work at each site, and don't assume what worked at Hospital A will work at Hospital B even if they run the same PACS.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FDA clearance is non-negotiable for clinical deployment in the US. Each indication (ICH, PE, pneumothorax) is typically a separate 510(k) submission. The regulatory timeline is 12-18 months per indication. If you're building this in-house rather than buying a cleared product, factor that into your roadmap. Most health systems buy rather than build for this reason.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that surprised me most: radiologists actually like these systems when they work well. The resistance is not to AI triage conceptually. It's to bad implementations that generate noise. Get the false positive rate below 5% and integrate cleanly into the existing worklist, and adoption follows naturally.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Quantitative reporting.** Beyond binary detection, add measurement capabilities: hemorrhage volume estimation, PE clot burden scoring, pneumothorax percentage. These quantitative outputs help radiologists prioritize within the "urgent" category and provide structured data for downstream clinical decision-making.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Longitudinal comparison.** For follow-up studies, automatically retrieve the prior study and run comparison inference. "New hemorrhage since prior" or "interval increase in effusion size" is more clinically actionable than a standalone detection. This requires patient matching and prior study retrieval from the archive, adding complexity but significant clinical value.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referring physician notification.** Extend the alerting beyond radiology. When a STAT finding is detected, automatically notify the referring/ordering physician (typically the ED attending for trauma cases). This closes the communication loop that the ACR critical results guidelines require, reducing the time from finding detection to clinical action.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
